# Relatos de Papel Cursor Rules

- Start from the nearest concrete file before changing anything.
- Keep the current Vite + React 19 + TypeScript + MUI architecture stable.
- Use functional components only.
- Use explicit TypeScript, typed mock data, and real custom hooks.
- Avoid `any`, `console.log`, dead code, and unused exports.
- Do not invent backend calls inside the frontend layer.
- Do not move route declarations out of `src/App.tsx`.
- Do not hardcode brand colors outside the theme.
- Do not create new global CSS unless the style is truly global.
- Reuse existing components, barrels, and theme tokens before creating new files.
- At the end of every AI-driven iteration, update [.github/copilot-instructions.md](.github/copilot-instructions.md), [.cursorrules](.cursorrules), [README.md](README.md), and [prompts.md](prompts.md) so the shared context and the user-facing guide stay synchronized.

## Scope map

### Root files

- `package.json`, `package-lock.json`, `vite.config.ts`, `eslint.config.js`, `tsconfig.json`, `tsconfig.app.json`, and `tsconfig.node.json` control build, lint, and TypeScript behavior.
- `index.html` is the app entry shell.
- `README.md` documents scripts, CI, and delivery expectations.
- `models.md` is the canonical domain model reference.
- `prompts.md` stores reusable prompts and AI context.
- `.env.example` is reserved for future environment variables only.

Future root documents:

- deployment notes or a Vercel URL file.
- video-memory support notes or delivery evidence.
- small feature planning notes.
- never commit generated builds, lockfile noise, or secrets.

### .github

- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` currently enforces lint and format checks.
- `.github/copilot-instructions.md` is the always-on workspace guidance.

Future `.github` folders:

- `.github/instructions/` for file-scoped rules.
- `.github/prompts/` for reusable prompts.
- `.github/agents/` for specialized workflows.
- `.github/skills/` for repeatable tool-driven tasks.
- more workflows only if they support CI, preview deploys, or release automation.

### src/App.tsx

- This is the single source of truth for routes.
- Keep public routes, protected routes, and fallback routes here.
- Keep React Router configuration declarative.

### src/root.tsx

- Bootstrap only.
- Import fonts, global CSS, StrictMode, and mount `App`.
- Keep business logic out of this file.

### src/root.css

- Global app styles only.
- Use it for resets, body background, and other truly global app-shell styles.
- Prefer MUI theme overrides for everything else.

### src/config/mui/

- `palette.ts` holds the brand colors only.
- `typography.ts` holds the Inter and Caveat stacks.
- `theme.ts` wires the palette, typography, shape, and component overrides.
- `index.ts` is the barrel export.

Future scope:

- add component overrides or theme tokens here when they are shared.
- never duplicate brand values in pages when they already belong in the theme.

### src/layouts/main/

- `Main.layout.tsx` owns the shell and `Outlet`.
- `Navbar.tsx` owns the sticky header and navigation affordances.
- `Footer.tsx` owns the footer and brand closure.
- `index.ts` should expose the layout entry point.

Future scope:

- keep persistent cart UI or shell-level badges here if they are shared across routes.
- split the shell before adding layout logic to pages.

### src/components/ui/

- `BrandIcon.tsx` is the brand mark.
- `Button.tsx` is currently a placeholder; if it stays, it must become a real typed wrapper or be replaced by MUI Button usage.
- `Examples.tsx` is the UI showcase, not production logic.
- `index.ts` is the barrel export.

Future scope:

- add reusable primitives here: empty states, section titles, price tags, stat cards, icon badges, search fields, and shared wrappers around MUI patterns.
- if more than one page needs a visual pattern, promote it here.

### src/components/book/

- `BookCard.tsx` is the book presentation component.
- `index.ts` is the barrel export.

Future scope:

- create `src/components/catalog/` if the catalog gains its own grid, filter, or result components.
- add book gallery or metadata helpers here before bloating the book page.

### src/context/

- `Auth.context.tsx` is currently a placeholder.
- `index.ts` is the barrel export.

Future scope:

- add `auth/`, `cart/`, `search/`, or `profile/` subfolders when each context needs its own provider, hook, and types.
- keep context values typed and stable.

### src/hooks/

- `api/use-api.hook.ts` is currently incomplete.
- Replace placeholder text with a real hook or retire it once feature hooks exist.

Future scope:

- `useAuth`, `useCart`, `useDebounce`, `useLocalStorage`, `useBookSearch`, `useCheckout`, and route-guard hooks belong here or in feature-specific hook folders.
- hooks should compose logic, not render UI.

### src/data/

- This folder is currently empty.
- Use it for typed mock data and in-memory fixtures.
- When generating large mock catalogs, use Open Library Search and Covers APIs as the upstream source, cache the responses, and persist the generated snapshot locally in `src/mocks/books.mock.ts`.
- Do not place live API fetches in pages just to populate mock content.
- Respect Open Library guidance: batch requests, identify the app with a `User-Agent`, and avoid bulk-download behavior or many single-book requests.

Future scope:

- add static datasets for books, customers, orders, categories, filters, and seeded examples.
- keep generators here or under `src/data/factories/` if test data generation is needed.
- do not mix data creation with page rendering.

### src/pages/

- Page files must stay thin and compose reusable components.
- `landing/Landing.page.tsx` is the public entry page.
- `login/Login.page.tsx` is the login form; success redirects to profile.
- `catalog/Catalog.page.tsx` is the title-only search and listing page.
- `book/Book.page.tsx` is the book detail page and the only place where a book can be added to the cart.
- `checkout/Checkout.page.tsx` is the protected checkout page.
- `profile/Profile.page.tsx` is the protected profile page with user data and the last five orders.
- `not-found/NotFound.page.tsx` is the route fallback.
- `story-book/StoryBook.page.tsx` is the component showcase.
- `index.ts` is the page barrel export.

Future scope:

- if a dedicated cart route is ever added, create `src/pages/cart/Cart.page.tsx`.
- if auth or admin screens appear later, create a new page folder only when the route is stable.
- keep business logic out of pages and move it into hooks, context, or reusable components.

### src/types/

- `book.types.ts`, `customer.types.ts`, and `order.types.ts` define the current domain model.
- `index.ts` is the shared export surface.

Future scope:

- add `auth.types.ts`, `cart.types.ts`, `filter.types.ts`, `ui.types.ts`, or `api.types.ts` only when those domains exist.
- keep types close to the feature, then export them through the barrel.

## Page contract

- Landing is public.
- Login must redirect to profile after success.
- Catalog filters by book title only for this activity.
- Only the book detail view may add a book to the cart.
- Cart must remain visible on catalog and book views.
- Checkout is protected and on success must call `window.alert`, clear the cart, then navigate to `/`.
- Profile is protected and must show user data plus the last five orders.
- NotFound must return the user to the app.
- StoryBook is for visual verification only.

## Styling contract

- Keep the current brand palette: navy primary, warm sand secondary, white contrast.
- Keep Inter for body text and Caveat for headings.
- Prefer MUI components, `sx`, and theme overrides over ad hoc CSS.
- Keep `src/root.css` for only global resets or truly global app-shell styling.
- Avoid generic default MUI screens; the app should feel book-themed, warm, and polished.
- If a reusable visual pattern appears more than once, promote it into `src/components/ui` or a domain component folder.

## Data and integration rules

- Use typed mock data until a backend exists.
- Do not add HTTP calls into pages as a shortcut.
- If network integration arrives later, create a dedicated `src/services/` or `src/api/` layer and keep pages thin.
- Keep search/filter logic client-side and title-only until the assignment changes.

## Future folders to create only when needed

- `src/components/catalog/`
- `src/components/cart/`
- `src/components/forms/`
- `src/components/profile/`
- `src/components/landing/`
- `src/components/auth/`
- `src/context/cart/`
- `src/context/search/`
- `src/hooks/useAuth.ts`
- `src/hooks/useCart.ts`
- `src/hooks/useDebounce.ts`
- `src/hooks/useLocalStorage.ts`
- `src/data/books.ts`
- `src/data/customers.ts`
- `src/data/orders.ts`
- `src/services/`
- `src/utils/`
- `src/constants/`
- `src/assets/`
- `src/test/` or `src/__tests__/`
- `.github/instructions/`, `.github/prompts/`, `.github/agents/`, `.github/skills/`

## Quality and validation

- Respect ESLint and Prettier; CI fails when lint or format fails.
- Avoid `any`, `console.log`, dead code, and unused exports.
- Keep components focused and easy to read.
- Update barrels when new modules are added.
- Validate the touched slice with the narrowest useful check before widening scope.
- If a change touches a shared contract, update every consumer of that contract.
